<br>
first)  At the time, and given the options currently available, and considering the method in which the US was drawn into the war (Pearl Harbor), I think that Truman believed that the bomb was the best method to end the war.<br>
<br>
second)  We were at war with an implacable foe, and by contemporary value judgements it was better that the Japanese die than Americans.<br>
<br>
third)  No one had ever used a nuclear weapon for that use before, and so the long-term effects could not be judged.<br>
<br>
fourth)  Dropping the bomb, while drastic, had the desired effect (to end the war).<br>
<br>
fifth)  We live in the 21st Century, not the 1940's.  As our lifespans have increased we have placed a greater value on life as a whole.  At the time, given the value we as Americans placed on life in general, and given the information available to the individuals in charge of the decision, it was a sound decision.<br>
<br>
sixth)  It was a tough decision.  And fate provide that I am never in the situation where I must weigh the lives of those, whose well-being is entrusted to me, against the lives of those who wish to destroy them.  Regardless of my decision, I would be judged a murderer.<br>
<br>
I hope this puts some perspective on the whole shebang. <p>Fritz Darkweaver<BR>
