Why? Because there's absolutely no kind of justification for that kind of destruction. It's akin to using a rocket launcher when a 9mm would have done the task.<br>
They can round up all sorts of statistics on how many would have potentially died. That is nearly the same as revisionist history because numbers like that can always be twisted to make them look like whatever the hell you want them to look like. Simple as that. We cannot know how many casualties there would have been at the time, nor today. However, at the time we knew how damn destructive those bombs were, and we REALLY know it today. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ufritzdarkweaver.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fritz Darkweaver</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif " BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Wedgie Avenger</span><br>  Posts: 94<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/30/01 5:29:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ending World War II</span><hr size=1> I'm not going to justify anything to you, ark.  I don't see the need to do so.<br>
<br>
And I appreciate and respect your belief that there is no good reason to use a nuclear weapon.  While I may not agree with it, it is your right to state and hold that opinion.<br>
<br>
It is my considered opinion (which is different than yours) that while in a state of war with a foe which had demonstrated the willingness to engage in wholesale slaughter and enslavement (the japanese campaigne into mainland china) that destroying two cities in order to force a surrender was preferrable to sending millions to die in order to achieve the same goal.<br>
<br>
Here is my reasoning, with which you will probably not agree, but is still my own opinion:<br>
<br>
I would die to stop a man from killing my child.<br>
I would die to stop a man from killing my neighbor's child.<br>
I would kill 1000 men to stop them from killing my child.<br>
I would kill 1000 men to stop them from killing my neighbor's child.<br>
By extension, I would kill 1,000,000,000 men to keep them from killing 1,000,000 of my neighbor's sons and daughters.<br>
<br>
It's not pretty, it's not neat and it's not particularly nice.  But it's the truth.  And I like to think that you would die to stop a man from killing your child, or to stop him from killing my child.  Maybe not.  That's a personal decision that I can't force.  However, based on my values it was the correct decision and I'll stand by those values to the end.<br>
<br>
As well, I believe the Japanese would not have hesitated to do the same had they had 'the bomb' first.  But as far as the decision to drop the bomb is concerned, I think that's a bit irrelevant. <p>Fritz Darkweaver<BR>
